Western leaders have opposed the eight per cent tax on petroleum products — down from 16 per cent — proposed by President Uhuru Kenyatta. Kakamega governor Wycliffe Oparanya and Senator Cleophas Malala have asked MPs to unite and reject the President’s proposal. They said it won’t help Kenyans. “The financial crisis in government is self-inflicted because the Jubilee administration engaged in poor budget making processes and budgeted beyond their means,” Oparanya said. Malala said MPs should serve the interests of Kenyans, not the President. “MPs should now not even talk of suspending but totally